                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Rio plea for terror shield
  - Bloodspill fear looms on Dimapur        OUR CORRESPONDENT                             A person injured in the NSCN (I-M) firing on Friday being taken to the hospital. Picture by Eastern Projections                                        
	Kohima, May 17: Apprehending more bloodshed between the different factions of the NSCN that are rushing in their cadre to Dimapur and Kohima, a worried Dimapur district administration today sought additional companies of security personnel to man the commercial hub that witnessed the killing of 15 persons by the Isak-Muivah faction of the outfit yesterday.         
	Around 5.30am yesterday, members of the NSCN (I-M) faction waylaid a joint team of the Khaplang and the Unification factions that was on a mission to raid their rivals camp at Seithekema C village outside Dimapur.        
	Though the situation in Dimapur remained by and large peaceful today, the streets were almost deserted.         
	Fears of a fresh run of terror following reports of the warring camps sending reinforcements on the outskirts of Dimapur for a showdown, has left the residents panic-stricken. According to sources, the NSCN (K) is spoiling for a fight to avenge the killing of its cadre.        
	The Dimapur district administration has asked for additional companies of police and India Reserve Battalion units to man Dimapur town.         
	With the invoking of prohibitory orders under Section 144 of the CrPC, vehicles went off National Highway 39, the lifeline of Manipur passing through Dimapur.        
	The Neiphiu Rio government has once again sent an SOS to the paramilitary forces, including the Assam Rifles and the CRPF, to enforce the ceasefire ground rules in conformity with the provisions of the standard operation procedures issued by the home ministry on January 29.         
	The Nagaland government has also urged the Centre to implement the ceasefire ground rules in toto.         
	The Angami Youth Organisation said it would not allow fratricidal killings in areas under its jurisdiction .         
	On Monday, the Opposition Congress will observe a 12-hour Dimapur bandh, beginning at 6am. Demanding central intervention, the parliamentary secretary of the Congress Legislature party, K.V. Pusa, said the state government had completely failed to solve the law and order problem.                                                                                                                                            
